eldest daughter of Jonathan Edwards."},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Eldest Edwards child born Sabbath afternoon, 1728","body":"She was born August 25, 1728 in Northampton — 'on a Sabbath day, between 2 and 3 o'clock in the afternoon,' as her father Jonathan Edwards recorded. She was the eldest of his eleven children."},{"number":2,"category":"marriage","header":"Married her father's attorney — Stockbridge farmer","body":"In 1750 she married Elihu Parsons, a Northampton attorney who handled many of Jonathan Edwards's legal and personal affairs. Parsons later farmed in Stockbridge, where the family settled during the Mohican mission years."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"Father warned suitor of her temper","body":"When Elihu Parsons asked Jonathan Edwards for her hand, Edwards reportedly disclosed her difficult temper before quipping: 'I hope she has grace, but grace can live where you cannot.'"},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Two daughters married into the Berkshire Ingersolls","body":"Two of her eleven children — both daughters — married into the Ingersoll family of Berkshire County, Massachusetts. This is a separate Ingersoll line from the Loyalist New Haven Ingersolls who descended through the Newton-Miles line."}],"slug":"sarah-edwards-1728"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}